<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the `sys_hub_flow` row that
    declares the `x_casemgmt_validate_inprogress_transition` Flow Designer
    SUBFLOW (type=subflow) inside the scoped application `x_casemgmt`
    (Case Management).

    PURPOSE (AAP Section 0.5.5 verbatim transition rows):
        From          To           Required condition / blocking-error behavior
        Open          In Progress  assigned_agent populated AND member of
                                   assigned_group.
                                   Failure: Surface form-level error
                                   "Assigned agent must be set and must be a
                                    member of the assigned group." (the
                                   uniform error message returned by the
                                   Script Include's canTransitionToInProgress
                                   guard for all three failure modes).
        Pending       In Progress  None additional; validator returns
                                   { ok: true } as long as assigned_agent
                                   is still set and still a member of
                                   assigned_group. The companion business
                                   rule x_casemgmt_clear_pending_reason_on_
                                   inprogress.xml is responsible for
                                   clearing the pending_reason field when
                                   the case re-enters In Progress; THIS
                                   subflow is concerned only with the
                                   precondition gate, not the side effect.

    This subflow is one of FIVE shared transition-validation subflows under
    `servicenow-case-management-poc/flows/sub_flows/`. Per AAP Section
    0.5.5, BOTH the Open -> In Progress AND the Pending -> In Progress
    transitions reuse this single subflow because their precondition is
    identical: assigned_agent must be populated AND must be a member of
    assigned_group. The validator's logic does not inspect the source
    status (Open vs Pending vs anything else); it inspects only the
    current values of assigned_agent and assigned_group on the case row.
    Therefore the parent flows can dispatch to THIS subflow regardless
    of the source status, and the subflow returns ok=true if the
    precondition holds or ok=false (with the verbatim error message)
    otherwise. This design honors AAP Section 0.5.5's instruction that
    Pending -> In Progress has "None" additional condition: the
    Pending-side parent flow path simply re-invokes the same gate, and
    the gate happens to pass automatically because Pending state was
    only reachable from In Progress (which itself required the gate to
    pass), so re-entering In Progress should also pass barring a manual
    deletion of assigned_agent or assigned_group between transitions.

    It is called by both parent state-machine flows whenever a case's
    `status` field changes to `In Progress`:

      - ../general_inquiry_state_machine.xml
            (when a General Inquiry case enters the In Progress status
             from either Open or Pending)
      - ../complaint_state_machine.xml
            (when a Complaint case enters the In Progress status from
             either Open or Pending)

    SEMANTIC SOURCE-SIDE REFERENCE (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported):

      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/
        java/com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/service/
        ChangeCaseFileStateService.java
            * line 79-114 changeCaseState(auth, caseId, newState,
              ipAddress) - the central case state-machine service in
              ArkCase. The single method covered every transition by
              string-matching the newState parameter and used a
              transactional write to update CaseFile.status. The
              ServiceNow target splits this into FIVE per-transition
              subflows; this subflow is the (Open|Pending) -> In
              Progress slice. The ArkCase method does NOT enforce
              the assigned_agent + group-membership precondition
              (that gate did not exist in ArkCase as a hard rule;
              the Activiti BPMN workflow assumed correct upstream
              assignment via separate forms). The ServiceNow target
              ADDS the explicit assigned_agent + group-membership
              gate per AAP Section 0.5.5, which strengthens the
              correctness model relative to ArkCase. Put differently,
              this subflow encodes a precondition that ArkCase
              relied on the workflow ENGINE to enforce indirectly;
              the ServiceNow target makes the precondition explicit
              and declarative.

      - acm-services/acm-service-users/src/main/java/com/armedia/acm/
        services/users/model/ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig.java
            ArkCase resolved privileges via a Map<String, List<Object>>
            keyed by role name; group membership was implicit via the
            user-to-role-to-privilege chain. The ServiceNow target
            uses the platform-native sys_user_grmember table for
            agent-to-group membership checks (encapsulated inside
            CaseTransitionValidator.isAgentInGroup); no privilege
            map is needed because group membership is the sole gate.

    SUBFLOW INPUTS (Flow Designer declarative parameters):

      1. case_record  (Reference to x_casemgmt_case, MANDATORY)
            Passed in by the parent flow as $trigger.current. This is
            the case row whose status is transitioning to In Progress
            (from either Open or Pending). The parent flow's OnUpdate
            trigger fires when status changes to 'In Progress', and
            the trigger's $trigger.current is the just-updated case
            GlideRecord. The Script Include's canTransitionToInProgress
            method uses caseGr.getValue('assigned_agent') and
            caseGr.getValue('assigned_group') to read the current
            field values, then calls isAgentInGroup(userSysId,
            groupSysId) to check membership in sys_user_grmember.
            All sys_id values used in the membership query are
            RUNTIME values (read from the case record at execution
            time), NOT hardcoded literals - this is the sole reason
            the "no hardcoded sys_ids" rule does not preclude the
            use of sys_id values inside this subflow's logic.

    SUBFLOW STEPS (ordered):

      Step 1: Validate In Progress Transition (assigned_agent + group
              membership check)
            A Script Step that:
                a) Instantiates the Script Include:
                       var validator = new x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator();
                b) Invokes the per-transition guard with the supplied
                   case_record GlideRecord:
                       var result = validator.canTransitionToInProgress(
                           fd_data.subflow_inputs.case_record);
                c) Exposes two outputs to the subflow execution context:
                       outputs.ok            = result.ok            (Boolean)
                       outputs.error_message = result.error || ''   (String)
            The Script Include's canTransitionToInProgress returns:
                { ok: true } - when assigned_agent is populated AND
                               assigned_group is populated AND the
                               agent is a member of the group
                { ok: false, error: 'Assigned agent must be set and must
                                     be a member of the assigned group.' }
                             - when assigned_agent is empty OR
                               assigned_group is empty OR the agent
                               is set but is NOT a member of the
                               group. The single uniform error message
                               is intentional: a probing client cannot
                               distinguish which precondition failed
                               (defense against privilege-escalation
                               reconnaissance).
                { ok: false, error: 'Case record is missing.' }
                             - when caseGr is null/undefined (defensive
                               guard inside the Script Include; should
                               not occur in normal parent-flow
                               invocation because the parent flow's
                               case_record input is mandatory).

      Step 2: If validator returned not-ok
            An If/Then condition that branches when:
                fd_data._step_outputs.step_run_validator.ok == false
            The branch contains a single Throw Error action.

      Step 2a: Throw Error (surfaces validator's message on form)
            The Throw Error action's message is bound to the Script
            Step's error_message output. At runtime, when the
            condition is true and the action fires, the platform:
                a) Calls gs.addErrorMessage(error_message) on the
                   current update transaction's session.
                b) Aborts the parent flow's triggering update
                   (the implicit setAbortAction(true) on Throw Error).
                c) Returns control to the form, which displays the
                   error message at the top of the form.
            The error message text is whatever the Script Include
            returned, which for THIS subflow is one of:
                "Assigned agent must be set and must be a member of the assigned group."
                "Case record is missing."
            (the first is the gate message for all three failure
            modes; the second is the defensive guard message). The
            message text is propagated through the Script Include's
            return value verbatim - this subflow does not compose
            its own message.

      Step 3: End (implicit success path)
            When the If condition evaluates to false (validator
            returned ok=true), no Throw Error fires and the subflow
            returns successfully to the parent flow. No outputs are
            exposed to the parent because the parent flow does not
            need a return value - the absence of a thrown error is
            the success signal. The parent flow then continues with
            the normal status-update path; the case's status field
            (set to 'In Progress' by the form save that triggered
            the parent flow) is preserved.

    OUTPUTS:
        None at the subflow level. The internal Script Step exposes
        ok and error_message outputs but those are scoped to the
        subflow and consumed only by the subsequent If/Throw Error
        step. The subflow itself returns no value to the parent.

    SCOPED-NAMESPACE CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):
        - <name>x_casemgmt_validate_inprogress_transition</name> uses
          the x_casemgmt scope prefix per the auto-assigned scoped-
          app namespace.
        - <sys_scope>x_casemgmt</sys_scope> binds THIS subflow record
          to the x_casemgmt scope.
        - <sys_package source="x_casemgmt">x_casemgmt</sys_package>
          binds THIS subflow record to the x_casemgmt application
          package.
        - The Flow Designer snapshot below references:
            * x_casemgmt_case table BY NAME
              (input parameter reference_table)
            * x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator Script Include BY
              API NAME (the canonical scope-qualified accessor for
              scoped Script Includes; see
              ../../script_includes/x_casemgmt_CaseTransitionValidator.xml
              <api_name>x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator</api_name>)
            * sys_user_grmember table indirectly (via the Script
              Include's isAgentInGroup which constructs new
              GlideRecord('sys_user_grmember') and addQuery() filters
              by user/group sys_ids read at runtime from the case
              row). sys_user_grmember is an OOB platform table that
              is read-only from this subflow's perspective; no
              modifications are made to it.
        Zero global-scope writes. Zero modifications to OOB tables
        (sys_user, sys_user_group, sys_user_role, core_company,
         task, incident, etc.). The sys_user_grmember READ is
         permitted because read access to OOB tables is not a
         "modification" - the AAP scope-bound rule (AAP Section
         0.7.2) prohibits WRITES to global tables, not READS.

    NO-HARDCODED-SYS_ID CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):
        - <sys_scope> resolves the scope record BY NAME (x_casemgmt)
        - <sys_package> resolves the application record BY NAME
          (x_casemgmt) via its `source` attribute
        - The subflow snapshot references the x_casemgmt_case table
          BY NAME ("reference_table": "x_casemgmt_case") and invokes
          the Script Include BY API NAME
          ("x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator"). Zero `sys_id`
          literal references appear anywhere in the snapshot or
          audit-field XML.
        - The <sys_id> element below is THIS record's own deterministic
          primary key (MD5 of "x_casemgmt_validate_inprogress_transition"),
          which is permitted because the AAP "no hardcoded sys_id" rule
          applies to REFERENCE FIELDS pointing at OTHER records, not to
          a record's own primary key. The deterministic derivation
          ensures idempotent re-import on a fresh PDI - re-importing
          the same Update Set produces the same sys_id, which collides
          on the existing record and updates it in place rather than
          creating a duplicate.
        - The Script Include's isAgentInGroup uses caseGr.getValue(
          'assigned_agent') and caseGr.getValue('assigned_group') to
          obtain runtime sys_ids - these are runtime values, not
          hardcoded literals.

    EMAIL-DISABLED CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):
        The subflow MUST NOT call gs.eventQueue('...') for any email
        notification event since email is disabled on the PDI. This
        subflow contains zero gs.eventQueue() calls, zero Send Email
        actions, and zero notification trigger steps. It performs
        only the validation-and-throw side effect on failure.
        Intentionally diverges from ArkCase ChangeCaseFileStateService
        line 106 raiseEvent() which would have triggered downstream
        notification listeners on every state change; the ServiceNow
        POC omits the equivalent call per the AAP minimal-change
        clause and the email-disabled constraint.

    NO PII (AAP Section 0.7.2):
        The description text, code comments, and snapshot inline
        labels contain zero real names, real email addresses, real
        phone numbers, real organizational identifiers, or any
        other personally identifiable information. The subflow
        operates exclusively on a case-row reference and emits a
        generic, AAP-aligned error string.

    ACTIVE-PUBLISHED STATE (CRITICAL per agent prompt Phase 2.3):
        - <active>true</active>      - subflow is enabled, NOT Draft
        - <status>published</status> - subflow is published, NOT draft
        Both are required for the parent flows to be able to call
        this subflow at runtime. A Draft-state subflow is callable
        only from the Flow Designer canvas during testing; published
        is the production-ready state.

    TYPE=SUBFLOW (CRITICAL per agent prompt Phase 2.4):
        - <type>subflow</type>
        Subflows are reusable building blocks called by parent flows
        via the "Call a Subflow" action. A type=flow record cannot
        be called by another flow; the platform looks for type=subflow
        records when resolving a "Call a Subflow" reference. The
        parent flows in ../general_inquiry_state_machine.xml and
        ../complaint_state_machine.xml reference this subflow BY
        NAME (x_casemgmt_validate_inprogress_transition), and the
        platform's lookup at activation time resolves to THIS record
        because of the type=subflow setting.

    RUN_AS=CALLER (CRITICAL per agent prompt Phase 2.4):
        - <run_as>caller</run_as>
        The subflow inherits the run-as context of the calling parent
        flow. The parent flows use run_as=user_who_triggers, so when
        the parent calls this subflow, the subflow ALSO runs as the
        triggering user. This ensures:
            * The Script Include's group-membership query in
              isAgentInGroup respects the caller's read ACL on
              sys_user_grmember (which is OOB-readable by all
              authenticated users, so this is generally a no-op
              constraint, but the run_as=caller setting guarantees
              correctness if ACLs are tightened later).
            * Any future audit logging tracks the actual user who
              attempted the In Progress transition, not the system
              account.

    DEFENSE-IN-DEPTH WITH BUSINESS RULE:
        The companion business rule
        ../../business_rules/x_casemgmt_validate_assigned_agent_membership.xml
        provides an additional layer: if assigned_agent is set but
        not a member of assigned_group, the BR rejects the save on
        EVERY save of the case row (not just status transitions to
        In Progress). This subflow is the FLOW-LEVEL guard that
        fires only on the (Open|Pending) -> In Progress transition;
        the BR is the FIELD-LEVEL guard that fires on every update.
        Together they ensure no path bypasses the precondition:
            - Form-driven In Progress transition: subflow catches it.
            - Direct Table API update setting status=In Progress
              with bad assigned_agent: subflow still catches it
              because the parent flow fires on OnUpdate.
            - Direct Table API update setting assigned_agent to a
              non-member while leaving status unchanged: BR catches
              it; subflow does not fire because status did not
              change.

    UPDATE-SET LOAD ORDER (AAP Section 0.5.2):

        This sys_hub_flow record MUST be loaded AFTER:

          - ../../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml
              (scoped application; <sys_package> reference resolution)
          - ../../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml
              (scope record; <sys_scope> reference resolution)
          - ../../tables/x_casemgmt_case.xml
              (parent table; the case_record input parameter is a
               Reference to this table)
          - ../../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_status.xml
              (the field whose change to 'In Progress' triggers the
               parent flow's OnUpdate filter; must exist before the
               parent flow's trigger filter can resolve)
          - ../../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_agent.xml
              (the field validated by the Script Include via
               caseGr.getValue('assigned_agent'); must exist before
               the validator can read it)
          - ../../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_group.xml
              (the field validated by the Script Include via
               caseGr.getValue('assigned_group'); must exist before
               the validator can read it)
          - ../../script_includes/x_casemgmt_CaseTransitionValidator.xml
              (the Script Include this subflow invokes; must exist
               and be activated before the subflow's Script Step can
               resolve the API name x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator)

        And BEFORE:

          - ../general_inquiry_state_machine.xml
              (parent flow that calls this subflow on the General
               Inquiry case-type's (Open|Pending) -> In Progress edges)
          - ../complaint_state_machine.xml
              (parent flow that calls this subflow on the Complaint
               case-type's (Open|Pending) -> In Progress edges)

    DETERMINISTIC SYS_ID:
        sys_id = MD5("x_casemgmt_validate_inprogress_transition")
               = f8117474ee1542c4e6aacd477fdef910
        32-character lowercase hex. The PDI accepts any valid 32-char
        hex sys_id; deriving from the record name guarantees idempotent
        re-import on a fresh PDI: re-importing the same Update Set
        produces the same sys_id, which collides on the existing
        record and updates it in place rather than creating a
        duplicate. This is the same convention used by every other
        deterministically-keyed record in this Update Set (e.g., the
        peer subflow validate_resolved_transition.xml whose sys_id is
        c8fde9d4675c53e1c14e40c0503835f0 = MD5 of
        "x_casemgmt_validate_resolved_transition", and
        validate_pending_transition.xml whose sys_id is
        94063d7d535c4e841ad7deb0b45e8ba5 = MD5 of
        "x_casemgmt_validate_pending_transition").

    VALIDATION GATE MAPPING (AAP Section 0.7.3):

        - Gate 2 (Workflow): "All state transitions enforced for both
          case types - Invalid transitions return blocking error;
          task-closure check blocks Resolved transition." THIS subflow
          contributes to Gate 2 by ENFORCING the assigned_agent +
          group-membership precondition for the (Open|Pending) -> In
          Progress transitions on BOTH case types (General Inquiry
          and Complaint). The gate is verified by:

              1) Create a case in 'Open' status with assigned_group
                 populated but assigned_agent EMPTY.
              2) Attempt to set the case's status to 'In Progress'
                 (e.g., via the form's Save button).
              3) The parent flow (general_inquiry or complaint
                 state_machine, depending on case.type) fires on
                 the OnUpdate trigger filtered to status -> In Progress.
              4) The parent flow calls this subflow with
                 case_record = $trigger.current.
              5) This subflow's Script Step runs the validator,
                 which detects assigned_agent is empty.
              6) The validator returns
                 { ok: false, error: 'Assigned agent must be set
                                       and must be a member of the
                                       assigned group.' }
              7) This subflow's If condition (ok == false) is true.
              8) The Throw Error action fires with the message.
              9) The parent flow's transaction aborts; the form
                 displays the error.
             10) The case row remains at status='Open' (the update
                 was rolled back; the new value 'In Progress' was
                 never persisted).

          Repeat with assigned_agent set to a user who is NOT a
          member of assigned_group: the validator returns the same
          error message because isAgentInGroup returns false.

          Repeat with assigned_agent set to a user who IS a member
          of assigned_group: the validator returns ok=true; the
          subflow returns; the parent flow proceeds; the status
          update is persisted; the case is now In Progress.

          Repeat the entire sequence for the Pending -> In Progress
          edge: the same gate fires, with the same outcomes.

        - Gate 7 (Update Set): "Scoped app exported - Update Set
          loads without errors on a fresh PDI instance." The
          deterministic sys_id, reference-by-name pattern, and well-
          formed XML structure ensure this record re-imports cleanly
          with zero preview errors. The CDATA-wrapped JSON snapshot
          contains characters requiring CDATA escaping (curly braces,
          quotes within JSON, the != comparison operator), and the
          CDATA section is properly opened and closed around both
          <latest_snapshot> and <master_snapshot> elements.

    PERFORMANCE NOTE:
        isAgentInGroup uses GlideRecord('sys_user_grmember') with
        addQuery('user', userSysId) and addQuery('group', groupSysId)
        followed by setLimit(1) and query() - the underlying SQL is
        a tightly-bounded indexed lookup that returns at most one
        row. For the Open -> In Progress transition, the validator
        does at most one row read from sys_user_grmember after the
        two field reads from the case row, so the gate path is
        extremely lightweight even at scale. There is no N+1 query
        anti-pattern: the validator does NOT iterate the agent's
        groups or the group's members.

    FUTURE EXTENSIBILITY:
        - If a future AAP enhancement adds a 'Reopened' status that
          allows transitions from Closed back to In Progress, this
          subflow would still apply (the validator is status-source-
          agnostic) and would still enforce the assigned_agent +
          group-membership gate. The gate is on the DESTINATION
          status (In Progress), not the source, so it transparently
          handles re-entry.
        - If group membership is later replaced by a more complex
          authorization model (e.g., a custom permission table or
          an LDAP group sync), only the Script Include's
          isAgentInGroup helper needs to change; this subflow
          continues to work unchanged because it consumes the
          unified { ok, error } shape returned by the validator.
        - If email is later re-enabled on the PDI and a "Case is
          now In Progress - assigned to [agent]" notification is
          desired, add a Send Email step to the parent flows
          (after the subflow returns successfully), NOT to this
          subflow. This subflow's responsibility is gating only;
          notification is a separate concern.
-->
